Cell["1.2 Properties of Probability", "Section",
 CellFrameColor->GrayLevel[0],
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.43533926749353*^9, 3.43533927429253*^9}},
 TextAlignment->Center,
 FontSize->14],

Cell["\<\
\tWe will begin this section with examples of the concrete construction of \
probability measures for sample spaces with finitely many outcomes.  With our \
feet on good intuitive ground, we will then be ready to set up a formal axiom \
system which permits rigorous proof of some important properties of \
probability. This is the way that most mathematical research actually \
proceeds: from concrete to abstract rather than the other way around. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.4562637356456003`*^9, 3.456263761058*^9}}],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Example 1",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "  If, as we said in Section 1.1, a probability measure gives likelihood to \
events, then at its most basic level it gives likelihood to simple events",
 ", that is, outcomes",
 ". As an example, I recently saw a breakdown of advanced placement scores \
for Illinois 12th graders on the subject test in English Language and \
Composition.  Scores range from 1 to 5, and the numbers of test takers in \
these categories for the particular year I looked at were:  1: 74, 2: 293, 3: \
480, 4: 254, 5: 130, for a total of 1231 students.  Consider first the random \
experiment of drawing a student at random from this group and observing the \
test score. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.40663977084375*^9, 3.406639776078125*^9}, 
   3.4562637892004004`*^9}],

