Cell["\<\
\tYou may be curious that the axioms only require events to have non-negative \
probability. It should also be clear that events must have probability less \
than or equal to 1, because probability 1 represents certainty. In the \
exercises you are asked to give a rigorous proof of this fact, stated below \
as Theorem 3. \
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Theorem 3",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ".  For any event ",
 StyleBox["A",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", P[",
 StyleBox["A",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "] \[LessEqual] 1.  ",
 "\[FilledSquare]"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.406650635234375*^9, 3.406650637171875*^9}}],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\tAnother intuitively obvious property is that if an event ",
 StyleBox["B",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " has all of the outcomes in it that another event ",
 StyleBox["A",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " has, and perhaps more, then ",
 StyleBox["B",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " should have higher probability than ",
 StyleBox["A",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". This result is given as Theorem 4, and the proof is Exercise 12."
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Theorem 4",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ".  If ",
 StyleBox["A",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["B",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " are events such that ",
 StyleBox["A ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "\[Subset] ",
 StyleBox["B",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", then P[",
 StyleBox["A",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "] \[LessEqual] P[",
 StyleBox["B",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "].  ",
 "\[FilledSquare]"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.4066506471875*^9, 3.4066506495625*^9}, 
   3.42341653403125*^9}],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\tTheorems 3 and 4 help to reassure us that our theoretical model of \
probability corresponds to our intuition, and they will be useful in certain \
proofs. But Theorems 1 and 2 on complements and unions are more useful in \
computations. We would like to finish this section by adding a third very \
useful computational result, usually called the ",
 StyleBox["Law of Total Probability",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". Basically it states that we can \"divide and conquer,\" that is break up \
the computation of a complicated probability P[",
 StyleBox["A",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "] into a sum of easier probabilities of the form P[",
 StyleBox["A",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "\[Intersection]",
 StyleBox["B",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "]. The imposition of condition ",
 StyleBox["B",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " in addition to ",
 StyleBox["A",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " presumably simplifies the computation by limiting or structuring the \
outcomes in the intersection. (See Figure 4.)  All of our computational \
results will be used regularly in the rest of the text, and the exercise set \
for this section lets you begin to practice with them."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.403886174265625*^9, 3.403886174453125*^9}, {
